EXPERIMENT 1 — EVEN/ODD + MULTIPLICATION TABLE
Original idea: Accept a number, check even/odd, print multiplication table 1 to 10.
================================================================================

1) Print table up to user-given limit
Why: Instead of fixed 1 to 10, user controls the range.

Code:
num = int(input("Enter number: "))
limit = int(input("Enter table limit: "))

for i in range(1, limit + 1):
    print(num, "x", i, "=", num * i)


2) Check whether number is positive, negative, or zero
Why: Adds one more if-elif-else condition check.

Code:
num = int(input("Enter number: "))

if num > 0:
    print("Positive number")
elif num < 0:
    print("Negative number")
else:
    print("Zero")


3) Check even/odd for multiple numbers
Why: Uses loop with list input instead of one number.

Code:
numbers = list(map(int, input("Enter numbers: ").split()))

for num in numbers:
    if num % 2 == 0:
        print(num, "is Even")
    else:
        print(num, "is Odd")


4) Print only even numbers from 1 to n
Why: Uses modulus condition inside loop.

Code:
n = int(input("Enter limit: "))

for i in range(1, n + 1):
    if i % 2 == 0:
        print(i)


5) Print multiplication table in reverse order
Why: Shows use of range() with negative step.

Code:
num = int(input("Enter number: "))

for i in range(10, 0, -1):
    print(num, "x", i, "=", num * i)


