EXPERIMENT 6 — FILE HANDLING + EXCEPTION HANDLING
Original idea: Write user string into file, read it back, handle errors.
================================================================================

1) Write instead of append
Why: 'w' replaces old content. 'a' adds to old content.

Code:
text = input("Enter text: ")

with open("data.txt", "w") as f:
    f.write(text)

print("Data written successfully")


2) Append multiple lines
Why: Adds new data without deleting old data.

Code:
text = input("Enter text: ")

with open("data.txt", "a") as f:
    f.write(text + "\n")

print("Data appended successfully")


3) Read file line by line
Why: Useful for large files.

Code:
try:
    with open("data.txt", "r") as f:
        for line in f:
            print(line.strip())
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found")


4) Count words in a file
Why: Common modification using string split().

Code:
try:
    with open("data.txt", "r") as f:
        data = f.read()
        words = data.split()
        print("Word count:", len(words))
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found")


5) Count characters in a file
Why: Uses len() on file content.

Code:
try:
    with open("data.txt", "r") as f:
        data = f.read()
        print("Character count:", len(data))
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found")


6) Use specific exception instead of plain except
Why: Better than using general except.

Code:
try:
    with open("data.txt", "r") as f:
        print(f.read())
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File does not exist")
except IOError:
    print("Input/output error occurred")


